<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ads-meta-targeting">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>ppc-manager</domain>
    <summary>Three-tier audience strategy: Core for cold, Custom for warm, Lookalike for scale. Build exclusion audiences before launch.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>meta-ads</tag>
      <tag>targeting</tag>
      <tag>audiences</tag>
      <tag>lookalike</tag>
      <tag>custom-audiences</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Meta Targeting &amp; Audiences</title>
    <summary>Three-tier audience strategy for Meta Ads: Core (interest/demographic/behavior) for cold traffic, Custom (pixel + email + engagement) for warm traffic, and Lookalike (1%, 2-3%, 5-10% of a quality source) for scaling. Build exclusion audiences (purchasers, subscribers) before launching any campaign. Use Advantage+ only for large budgets with broad-appeal products; manual targeting for niche or small budgets.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Audience quality is a direct multiplier on CPA — showing ads to the wrong people converts at 0.2% instead of 2%, a 10x cost difference. Lookalike audiences built from purchasers (not visitors) produce the highest-quality cold traffic. Excluding converters prevents wasted spend and audience pollution in prospecting campaigns.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up audiences before launching any Meta campaign.</item>
        <item>Scaling a campaign by expanding from Core/Interest to Lookalike.</item>
        <item>Building retargeting audiences by pixel behavior (pricing page, cart, checkout).</item>
        <item>Testing which audience type produces the lowest CPA (Core vs LAL vs retarget).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Audience size below 500K for Core/Interest — ad delivery is constrained and CPM spikes.</item>
        <item>Lookalike with a source smaller than 1,000 people — match quality is poor; build up the source first.</item>
        <item>Advantage+ when the product is niche or the budget is small — Meta's AI needs scale to work.</item>
        <item>When pixel is not installed and verified — Custom and Lookalike audiences won't populate correctly.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Core Audiences">
      <p>Core audiences target cold traffic by demographics, interests, and behaviors. Components: Location, Age, Gender, Languages, Interests (hobbies/brands/topics), Behaviors (purchase behavior, device use), Demographics (job title, education, life events).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Minimum Core audience size is 500K; ideal range is 1-5M. Below 500K, CPM spikes and delivery becomes constrained.</statement>
        <rationale>Meta's ad auction requires sufficient audience depth to find the right users at a competitive price. Too narrow and the algorithm cannot optimize; CPM rises sharply and reach plateaus.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Interest targeting strategy: start with 5-10 related interests. Finding relevant interests: competitor brands, industry publications, related tools the audience uses, communities they belong to.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Custom Audiences">
      <p>Custom audiences use first-party data: website pixel events, email lists, app activity, video engagement, lead form interactions, Facebook/Instagram page engagement.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Install and verify the Meta Pixel with standard events before creating any website custom audience.</statement>
        <rationale>Without pixel events firing correctly, website audiences will not populate or will include the wrong users. Verify event completeness in Events Manager before launch.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Website audience segments ranked by intent: Purchasers (180d) → Add to cart (7d) → Pricing page (14d) → Product page (30d) → Blog visitors (60d) → All visitors (180d).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always create exclusion audiences (purchasers, active subscribers) before running acquisition campaigns.</statement>
        <rationale>Showing acquisition ads to existing customers wastes spend and degrades ad relevance scores. Exclusions also prevent the algorithm from optimizing toward already-converted users who inflate conversion metrics without representing net-new customers.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Lookalike Audiences">
      <p>Lookalike audiences let Meta find users similar to a source audience. Percentages: 1% = highest quality/smallest, 2-3% = balanced, 5-10% = scale/lower quality.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use purchasers or high-value customers as the Lookalike source, not all website visitors.</statement>
        <rationale>The source audience defines the match pattern. Visitors include bounced traffic and irrelevant browsers; purchasers are the highest-quality signal. A LAL from visitors finds people who might visit; a LAL from purchasers finds people who might buy.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Best source audiences ranked: 1) Purchasers/customers, 2) High-value customers, 3) Leads who converted, 4) Website visitors with action, 5) Email subscribers.</item>
        <item>Minimum source size: 1,000 people. Ideal: 2,000-10,000. More data = better matching.</item>
        <item>Strategy: LAL_Purchasers_1% for best quality, LAL_Purchasers_2-3% for balance, LAL_Purchasers_5-10% for scale.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Audience Size Guidelines">
      <list>
        <item>Core/Interest: minimum 500K, ideal 1-5M.</item>
        <item>Custom source: minimum 1,000, ideal 5,000+.</item>
        <item>Lookalike output: 500K-2M depending on country.</item>
        <item>Retargeting: minimum 1,000, ideal 10,000+.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Testing Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Test 3-5 audience types simultaneously with identical creatives and equal budget; identify the lowest-CPA winner before scaling.</statement>
        <rationale>Audiences with different creatives confound results — it is impossible to attribute performance differences to the audience or the ad. Identical ads isolate the audience variable. Equal budget ensures each audience gets a fair trial before the algorithm can over-optimize toward one.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Audience test structure with identical ads across all ad sets.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Campaign: Audience Testing
├── Ad Set: Interest_Tech (same 3 ads)
├── Ad Set: Interest_Startup (same 3 ads)
├── Ad Set: LAL_Purchasers_1% (same 3 ads)
├── Ad Set: LAL_Purchasers_2-3% (same 3 ads)
└── Ad Set: Retarget_PricingPage_14d (same 3 ads)

Run 7+ days, minimum $20/day per ad set.
Winner = lowest CPA with statistically sufficient conversions.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <p>Testing progression: Start broad (3-5 types), find winner, expand within winning type, create LALs from best performer, repeat.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Audience Layering">
      <p>Combine targeting dimensions for precision using AND logic in Meta's audience builder. Example for B2B SaaS: Interests in SaaS AND Job Title Founder/CEO AND Behavior Business page admin.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use AND layering to increase precision only when the resulting audience remains above 500K; otherwise the audience is too narrow for efficient delivery.</statement>
        <rationale>AND layers multiply exclusions. Three layers each removing 70% of the audience leaves 2.7% of the original pool — often below the delivery threshold that causes CPM to spike.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Layering 4+ interest and behavior dimensions on a small-country audience.</description>
        <reason>The resulting audience may be too small for efficient delivery. Meta requires sufficient scale to find the right users at competitive auction prices.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Exclusion Strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Exclude recent purchasers from all acquisition campaigns; exclude current trial users from trial acquisition campaigns; exclude leads from lead generation campaigns.</statement>
        <rationale>Without exclusions, acquisition campaigns optimize toward existing customers (easiest to convert because they already know the brand), producing inflated conversion metrics that do not represent new customer acquisition.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Exclusion windows: Purchases — exclude for 30-90 days then upsell. Trial start — exclude until trial ends. Lead form submission — exclude until sales follow-up complete.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Advantage+ vs. Manual Targeting">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Advantage+ Audience for large budgets (over $100/day) with broad-appeal products; use manual targeting for niche products, small budgets, or when retargeting specific segments.</statement>
        <rationale>Advantage+ needs scale to work — its AI requires sufficient conversion data to learn effectively. Niche products benefit from human-defined constraints that prevent the algorithm from drifting to irrelevant but easily-reachable users.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Integration &amp; Automation">
      <p>Programmatic build/refresh of Meta Custom Audiences from CRM, pixel, or warehouse data on a schedule. Auto-generate Lookalike audiences (1 / 2-3 / 5-10%) when a source segment crosses the 1k-seed threshold. Maintain exclusion audiences (recent purchasers, paid trials, churned) so prospecting ad sets do not double-charge.</p>
      <p>Build structured audience-test campaigns (3-5 ad sets, identical creative) and wait for statistical significance before promoting winners. Reconcile audience size/overlap reports across Meta Ads Manager + a data warehouse (BigQuery / Snowflake).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Hash PII client-side with the exact recipe Meta documents (lowercase, trim, SHA-256). Mismatched hashes silently drop match rate from approximately 70% to less than 10%.</statement>
        <rationale>Meta's PII matching is deterministic. Even small variations in normalization cause the hash to mismatch and the record to be dropped from the audience. Exact compliance is required.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Pair every pixel event with a CAPI event using the same event_id for deduplication; without it, retargeting audiences halve post-iOS. Refresh seed audiences weekly, regenerate Lookalikes monthly. Stale LAL drifts off ICP.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Known Limitations &amp; Gotchas">
      <p>iOS 14.5+ ATT erodes pixel-only retargeting; without CAPI + offline conversions, custom audiences shrink 30-60%. Agents that only manage pixel events will silently degrade.</p>
      <p>Lookalike quality drops sharply when source is less than 1k or source is skewed (e.g. 90% one country). Agent must sanity-check source distribution before creating LAL.</p>
      <p>Audience overlap greater than 25% inside one campaign causes Meta to suppress one ad set. Agent must run Audience Overlap report and dedupe before launch.</p>
      <p>Advantage+ Audience often ignores manual exclusions when "Audience suggestion" is enabled — agent must verify exclusions stuck after each save. Custom Audience minimum (1k) is enforced silently — uploads below threshold appear "Ready" but never deliver.</p>
      <p>Marketing API errors return HTTP 200 with an error sub-object. Naive agents treat 200 as success and silently fail. Always inspect error.code / error.subcode.</p>
      <p>CustomAudience creation is async — approximate_count_lower_bound is null for up to 24h. Do not trigger LAL creation in the same run; queue it for a follow-up job.</p>
      <p>Special Ad Categories block lookalike + most targeting fields. The API accepts the create call then silently ignores fields. Agent must read back the audience and verify.</p>
      <p>Token rotation: long-lived system-user tokens still expire on permission changes. Build retry-on-190 (token expired) into the agent, but require human re-auth — never store user passwords.</p>
      <p>Meta deprecates targeting options without notice (e.g. detailed-targeting categories collapsed in 2022). Agent prompts that hardcode interest IDs break silently. Pin a quarterly review checkpoint where a human re-validates the targeting taxonomy.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices for Targeting">
      <p>Always add a "purchasers 90-180d" exclusion to every prospecting ad set as a campaign-level default, not per ad set — humans forget; agents should enforce in code.</p>
      <p>Keep audience names schema-encoded: &lt;purpose&gt;_&lt;source&gt;_&lt;window&gt;_&lt;version&gt; (e.g. LAL_purchasers_1pct_v3). Lets the agent diff against a registry deterministically.</p>
      <p>Run Audience Overlap report before launch when running more than 3 ad sets in one campaign. Do not let the agent run free on budget changes — gate any spend-affecting mutation behind a human approval step or a hard daily budget cap.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/custom-audience-library.md" purpose="Checklist of website, engagement, customer, and exclusion audiences to create."/>
      <template path="templates/audience-testing-log.md" purpose="Audience test tracking table with spend, conversions, CPA, and winner decision."/>
    </templates>
